<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">
The calling song contains two types of phrases (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 58" captionStartId="F5781459" captionText="Figure 58. Calling song of Oligoglena tibialis. (A) spectrogram and oscillogram of the calling song, showing the transition from the first phrase to the second; (B) oscillogram of the enlarged part of the transition from the first phrase to the second one corresponding to the inverted window in (A)." figureDoi=".figure58" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/407066" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">58</figureCitation>
). The first phrase (duration 920 
<normalizedToken originalValue="±">+/-</normalizedToken>
89 ms) is a sequence of short echemes (SE) (duration 48 
<normalizedToken originalValue="±">+/-</normalizedToken>
8 ms) followed by a long echeme (LE) (duration 292 
<normalizedToken originalValue="±">+/-</normalizedToken>
50 ms). Usually groups of short first phrases with 2-5 SE are separated by longer first phrases with a higher number of SE (11-13), but there is little regularity in this pattern. The second phrase consists of regularly repeated SE (duration 54 
<normalizedToken originalValue="±">+/-</normalizedToken>
11 ms, 38-76 SE) (
<bibRefCitation author="Gogala, Matija" journalOrPublisher="Acta Entomologica Slovenica" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424" pagination="45 - 62" refId="B5742895" refString="Gogala, Matija, Popov, Andrej V, Ribaric, D, 1996. Bioacoustics of singing cicadas of the western Palaearctic: Cicadetta tibialis (Panzer) (Cicadoidea: Tibicinidea). Acta Entomologica Slovenica 42 (2): 45 - 62" title="Bioacoustics of singing cicadas of the western Palaearctic: Cicadetta tibialis (Panzer) (Cicadoidea: Tibicinidea)" volume="42" year="1996">Gogala et al. 1996</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Joermann, G" journalOrPublisher="Zoologischer Anzeiger" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424" pagination="283 - 296" refId="B5743140" refString="Joermann, G, Schneider, H, 1987. The songs of four species of cicada in Yugoslavia (Homoptera: Cicadidae). Zoologischer Anzeiger 219 (5/6): 283 - 296" title="The songs of four species of cicada in Yugoslavia (Homoptera: Cicadidae)" volume="219" year="1987">Joermann and Schneider 1987</bibRefCitation>
). The first phrase could last for minutes, then the animal suddenly switches to a second phrase, which could last only a few or ten seconds, then the first phrase appears again. It has often been observed that, after the second phrase, the males stopped singing and flew away. The spectrum of the calling song contains two frequency bands: a main band between 12 and 22 kHz with a maximum between 14 and 18 kHz and sometimes with a secondary peak near 12 kHz and a second band with a maximum between 7 and 8 kHz (
<bibRefCitation author="Gogala, Matija" journalOrPublisher="Acta Entomologica Slovenica" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424" pagination="45 - 62" refId="B5742895" refString="Gogala, Matija, Popov, Andrej V, Ribaric, D, 1996. Bioacoustics of singing cicadas of the western Palaearctic: Cicadetta tibialis (Panzer) (Cicadoidea: Tibicinidea). Acta Entomologica Slovenica 42 (2): 45 - 62" title="Bioacoustics of singing cicadas of the western Palaearctic: Cicadetta tibialis (Panzer) (Cicadoidea: Tibicinidea)" volume="42" year="1996">Gogala et al. 1996</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
